Greetings! We are still working on many things. Albeit the new offseason robot progress is slow there are many things that we do.

We got our outreach robot all* fixed up and its ready to shoot notes at our misbehaving members again! (For legal reasons thats a joke)(Also the notes are very soft and do not hurt) *One of the pizza ring Falcon 500‚Äôs has very low torque (could be burnt up?) and has made the omni feeding very hard

Unfortunately, there will be no Robots@CNE this year, as a team we are grief-stricken.

But we are excited for Robots@ ! Thank you to the team there for all that they do to make this event happen.

We have finalized the BOM for the competition robot. Other than that no other updates, keeping our fingers crossed for when Kraken x44‚Äôs and x60‚Äôs to come back in stock soon so we can snag some for our robot.

By technicality, our team was 1 week behind schedule now that Robots@? has been pushed back we are 2 weeks ahead of schedule. Work slower and you‚Äôll be rewarded with more time. But in all/half seriousness if we keep this pace up we will either be around 10 weeks behind schedule or 20+ weeks ahead of schedule.

We have assembled all stages and found out our string isn‚Äôt long enough. Stay tuned for following updates, here‚Äôs a video in the meantime:

We blew up our climber‚Ä¶ however we adjusted our string attachment method and it works now. Video of it working:

TL;DR: Got a lot of parts done and they have pasted the motor driven tests, we are making good progress to finishing this project. Thanks to Sable and Tri-M for cutting these parts. (Lots of heavy cheesing involved)

Continuous Style Elevator With rope works, this was our first year doing a elevator in our main season and it‚Äôs great that we are moving to using a continuous elevator.

Intake is fast, it can pick up coral from many different orientations, only tripe is that it is bulkier than other similar ground intakes, but it works. Waiting on Metal plates for it.

Super Pinch works with the krakenx44, it‚Äôs quite secure, the belt is in the tube to avoid damage and it looks nicer.

posts.name: Aaron Huang
posts.cooked:
Our robot is nearly entirely assembled! Aside from a hiccup involving our climber (the rope snapped and the MAXtube exploded again), Jetstream is good to go! We have run some tests and all of our subsystems work together! This is very exciting as this is our most advanced bot yet, with the most amount of cheesing and custom parts! Also, CNC router.

We identified a failure point in our bot, which happens if the coral falls in the coral basket sideways. With the climber installed, it is probably going to be near impossible to shake the coral out. While this is very unlikely, as it would require both missing a coral and said coral falling perfectly into the basket, if it happens we would just be turned into an algae bot.

posts.name: Ben
posts.cooked:
AaronHuang:

We identified a failure point in our bot, which happens if the coral falls in the coral basket sideways. With the climber installed, it is probably going to be near impossible to shake the coral out. While this is very unlikely, as it would require both missing a coral and said coral falling perfectly into the basket, if it happens we would just be turned into an algae bot.

I think that adding some blocks in that space will solve the problem. I‚Äôm assuming that you have the cutout in your coral basket to allow your claw to come in and grab the coral easier. If you add an elevation to one side and then add little triangle ramp pieces, you should be able to knock coral out of that space.

Basically adding elevation to one side of the coral prevents it from getting fully jammed in that space, so that you can knock it put of the robot.
